    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-11T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-11T13:00:00-05:00" n="523"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d523">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.5/12–1151: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_GWS1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gifford</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d523fn1">This telegram was repeated for information to
                        Paris.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-11T18:00:00+00:00"
                            >December 11, 1951—6 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2684. In conversation with <persName corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName> this
                    morning I raised question of <gloss target="#t_EDF1">EDF</gloss>. He said Brit
                    position was unchanged, so far as putting troops in <gloss target="#t_EDF1"
                        >EDF</gloss> was concerned and that he had discussed matter with <persName
                        corresp="#p_MAFMVBLM1">Montgomery</persName> who had urged him to keep to
                    this position. He added that he appreciated very much <persName
                        corresp="#p_ADG1">Acheson</persName>’s message to him of December 7 (Paris
                    tel to Dept 3398, December 7<note n="2" xml:id="d523fn2">Not printed; it
                        transmitted the text of Secretary <persName corresp="#p_ADG1"
                            >Acheson</persName>’s personal message of December 8 to Foreign
                        Secretary <persName corresp="#p_EA1">Eden</persName>, <ref target="#pg_955"
                            >p. 955</ref>. (740.5/12–751)</note>) and that he and <persName
                        corresp="#p_CWS1">Churchill</persName> expect to do everything they can to
                    help support <gloss target="#t_EDF1">EDF</gloss>, short of agreeing to actual
                    Brit participation, when they are in France on 17th and 18th of this month. He
                    said that if in spite of all efforts <gloss target="#t_EDF1">EDF</gloss> did not
                    materialize, he was considering what new approach to problem might be
                    proposed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GWS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gifford</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
